text:
samtalskontakten ringde igår. hon hade tydligen varit sjuk i en månad. bokat tid på måndag.
tydligen vet hon inte alls vad hennes uppgift ska/kommer vara.
vi får se hur det går med samtalskontakten, hur planeringen blir och om den följs.
jag har absolut inga förväntningar alls.
tragiskt nog så har jag verkligen inget förtroende överhuvudtaget för psykiatrin. de har varit duktiga på att lova guld och gröna skogar, både på möten och i vårdplaneringar men min erfarenhet är att deras löften och ord är lika pålitliga som politikernas löften och ord. 
jag försöker att inte vara negativ, jag försöker att gå in med om inte positiv, så åtminstone en neutral inställning. 
har börjat få tillbaka mycket minnen och mardrömmar igen från tiden med niklas. glåporden, pikarna om sexlivet inför hans kompisar, manipulationen, alla de sätt han lyckades trycka ner mig på och alla sätt han lyckades utnyttja mig på. 
det sexuella... jag gör allt i min makt för att undvika att minnena dyker upp. men det räcker att ordet våldtäkt nämns på facebook eller på tv så snurrar hjärnan igång direkt.
jag känner mig så fruktansvärt korkad och dum. vi hade ju knappast ett lugnt och harmoniskt förhållande och jag kastade ut honom flertalet gånger. ändå tog jag tillbaka honom gång på gång. hur kan man vara så urbota dum.
jag gick i tankar att tala om för honom att det känns fel och jobbigt när han gett sig på mig när jag sovit eller när han tjatat och gett mig dåligt samvete över just sexlivet. men jag tordes inte. jag trodde jag överdrev, jag trodde att jag såklart var tvungen att ställa upp. hans ord "en karl behöver vad en karl behöver", "det är inte lika roligt eller skönt att dra en runk". jag trodde inte jag hade något val.  det var ju mig det var fel på som inte frivilligt släppte till tillräcklig ofta.... känslorna. självhatet och föraktet mot mig själv, över hur jag kunde vara så urbota dum och korkad. jag har skrikit och slagits, jag har bytt rum/våning, jag har t.o.m jagats ut ur mitt eget hem för att freda mig själv. jag har även gett upp och bara tänkt att det är över snart, då kan jag duscha och lägga mig på soffan och sova. känner mig så korkad som "tillät" det ske gång på gång...
name: min_mammas_2_barns_storasyster

tydligen vet hon inte alls vad hennes uppgift ska/kommer vara.
vi får se hur det går med samtalskontakten, hur planeringen blir och om den följs.
jag har absolut inga förväntningar alls.
tragiskt nog så har jag verkligen inget förtroende överhuvudtaget för psykiatrin. de har varit duktiga på att lova guld och gröna skogar, både på möten och i vårdplaneringar men min erfarenhet är att deras löften och ord är lika pålitliga som politikernas löften och ord. 
jag försöker att inte vara negativ, jag försöker att gå in med om inte positiv, så åtminstone en neutral inställning. 
har börjat få tillbaka mycket minnen och mardrömmar igen från tiden med niklas. glåporden, pikarna om sexlivet inför hans kompisar, manipulationen, alla de sätt han lyckades trycka ner mig på och alla sätt han lyckades utnyttja mig på. 
det sexuella... jag gör allt i min makt för att undvika att minnena dyker upp. men det räcker att ordet våldtäkt nämns på facebook eller på tv så snurrar hjär igång direkt.
jag känner mig så fruktansvärt korkad och dum. vi hade ju knappast ett lugnt och harmoniskt förhållande och jag kastade ut honom flertalet gånger. ändå tog jag tillbaka honom gång på gång. hur kan man vara så urbota dum.
jag gick i tankar att tala om för honom att det känns fel och jobbigt när han gett sig på mig när jag sovit eller när han tjatat och gett mig dåligt samvete över just sexlivet. men jag tordes inte. jag trodde jag överdrev, jag trodde att jag såklart var tvungen att ställa upp. hans ord "en karl behöver vad en karl behöver", "det är inte lika roligt eller skönt att dra en runk". jag trodde inte jag hade något val.  det var ju mig det var fel på som inte frivilligt släppte till tillräcklig ofta.... känslorna. självhatet och föraktet mot mig själv, över hur jag kunde vara så urbota dum och korkad. jag har skrikit och slagits, jag har bytt rum/våning, jag har t.o.m jagats ut ur mitt eget hem för att freda mig själv. jag har även gett upp och bara tänkt att det är över snart, då kan jag duscha och lägga mig på soffan och sova. känner mig så korkad som "tillät" det ske gång på gång...

text:
i believe quite a few things.

i believe the #metoo campaign didn't reveal what was new, but what has always been there. i believe what's sad are not only the stories, but the subtle cultures and behaviours which have allowed this to happen, in the church and outside. ranging from subtle cultures which promote that women are the cause of men falling, to misinterpreted scriptures to a lack of accountability. i believe the church must be involved in these conversations. not just to discuss the stories, but to discuss everything around the stories, that allowed these stories to become a reality.

my team and i have had this in the works for a while. not another lecture, but an open forum interactive conversation to discuss this. there will be a panel discussion at the beginning of the night (which i will be on, alongside two amazing women), but more of the night will be dedicated to having a conversation. we initiated this conversation at @god_ldn's most recent meet up (the lounge) to find out the questions and thoughts on the mind of our young adults (and there are a lot), but we've dedicating a whole night to this. learning from each other. examining the scriptures to see where they have been abused and how they call us to accountability. purity culture and whether we've gone about it the right way. and more.

so would love to see you there. especially christian men. we have said for so long that men must be involved in these conversations. we have said that men most hold each other accountable. this is an opportunity to.

link to tickets in @god_ldn's bio.

#churchxmetoo
#metoo
#churchtoo

text:
#ladies, take a look at handsoffix.org & get ready to be angry! i don’t associate with either political party, but the proposed changes to title ix make me mad. our secretary of education is proposing new rules on how schools handle sexual assault such as: • •colleges no longer required to move perpetrators from the survivor’s dorm & classes •schools allowed to delay investigations indefinitely •colleges allowed to just investigate whatever they determine to be the most “serious” cases •
•so...make sure you are registered to vote!!! 🇺🇸

text:
in a recent study most teens said they know what a healthy relationship is, but they don’t expect to be in one. 
wow.

we can change that.

imagine a world where:

teens know that they are loved and how to love,
gender doesn’t define how we treat each other, and
everyone experiences healthy, loving, and safe relationships.

are you ready to take action?

share some info from this link 👇🏾 on your social with one of these 🍭super sweet 🍭valentines! ❤️ https://wscadv.org/projects/preventing-violence/

february is teen dating violence action month! 💥 we all have a role to play in creating this world and ending domestic violence.

-

text:
today marks #blackhistorymonth. we wanted to celebrate the legacy sojourner truth. she was was born into slavery at the end of the 18th century and managed to escape from her captors in 1826: “i did not run off, for i thought that wicked, but i walked off, believing that to be all right.” she soon converted to methodism and began campaigning for women’s rights and the abolition of slavery.
.
in 1851 she gave her famous, improvised speech “ain’t i a woman” at the ohio women’s rights convention in akron. more than 150 years later, the message of sojourner’s speech still rings true: we must give more space to women of color in our feminist movements and that women have the strength, power, and vision to change the world.
.
“that man over there says that women need to be helped into carriages, and lifted over ditches, and to have the best place everywhere. nobody ever helps me into carriages, or over mud-puddles, or gives me any best place! and ain’t i a woman? look at me! look at my arm! i have ploughed and planted, and gathered into barns, and no man could head me! and ain’t i a woman? i could work as much and eat as much as a man - when i could get it - and bear the lash as well! and ain’t i a woman? i have borne thirteen children, and seen most all sold off to slavery, and when i cried out with my mother’s grief, none but jesus heard me! and ain’t i a woman?
.
then that little man in black there, he says women can’t have as much rights as men, ‘cause christ wasn’t a woman! where did your christ come from? where did your christ come from? from god and a woman! man had nothing to do with him.”
name: Ruman Project

reposted from @lagosshapers -  in the late 1950s, tampons were available to women but they were frowned upon. it was even considered “indecent” to wear them at the time. cloths or different types of ranges were used but that method was unsanitary and inconvenient. .

enter mary kenner, a black inventor from monroe, north carolina, who was inspired by her father to discover new things. in 1956, she invented the sanitary belt, which basically gave women a better alternative for dealing with their periods.

the sanitary belts also included moisture proof napkin pockets for comfort. it didn’t become a patent until 30 years after she had invented it. the company that was initially interested in the invention rejected her once they found out she was black. .

in 1982, kenner obtained a patent for an improved version of the bathroom tissue holder. her design kept the loose end of the tissue role away from the body. mrs. kenner‘s goal was never to make a lot of money, and her mission was to make peoples lives easier through her inventions. -- .
.
#dang #danghero
.
.

text:
welcome to february, which is #blackhistorymonth here in the united states. we’re celebrating by recognizing the black women who worked tirelessly (often without recognition) to bring black issues to the forefront.
————
black women have been the groundswell behind every social justice movement in this country (probably because, as research suggests, we’re more likely to be dehumanized and objectified 🤷🏾‍♀️). from abolition to women’s suffrage, from civil rights to labor rights to #metoo, black women have worked tirelessly to change the status quo and dismantle systems of oppression.
————
for the next 3 friday’s in february, we’ll share the stories of incredible black women who fought (and continue to fight) against injustice in this country.  because her story is our history ✊🏿✊🏾✊🏽✊🏼

i was reading an article today regarding marc emery being dropped from a cannabis event in argentina and i wanted to share this fabulous quote regarding the #metoo and #timesup movements finally making their way into the cannabis world: "the struggle for the decriminalization of drugs is incompatible with people who represent patriarchal schemes of subjection of women. the cannabis militants seek the equality, request and freedom that the feminist movement pursues." — pablo ferreyra 
the full article can be found here: goo.gl/psbza3

text:
💋💄👄pucker up👄💄💋 so once it was tiny waist big hips
then it was being stick thin 
then it was huge boobs 
then it was curvy bums 
then it was big lips 💋💋💋 big lips are the thing right now. the number of women getting lip fillers has increased hugely over the past few years. my view, this is largely driven by us seeing enhanced lips sooooo much it’s almost considered normal. 💉firstly, make sure this is what you really want, not what celebrity culture has driven into you
💉if it is what you want, please please see a qualified practitioner... you cannot cover up a bodged job on your face
💉if you are even slightly unsure about the decision or the practitioner, pause, give yourself time to re think

what’s the next cosmetic ‘must have’ for women? i’m still gunning for the ‘mum bod’..... 🙌

#selflove #feminist #bodypositive #equality #society #women #ladies #surgery #lips #lipfillers #cosmeticsurgery #empowerment #empoweringwomen #feminism #beautytrends #rights #confidence #metoo #beauty

text:
i gave this book 3 stars. i really enjoyed the idea behind the premise, and the strength of the girls in this story as they worked to right some awful wrongs and ended up healing in their own unique ways. .
content and trigger warnings: for rape, rape culture, sexual assault, physical abuse, emotional abuse and grief.
.
the friendships between thea and her black coats team made this book. i loved the way in which colleen wove their stories together and showed how strong friendships can blossom between the unlikeliest of people. this story really reminded me that we are always more alike than we think. the romance was fun, but i liked that it didn’t take away from thea’s main purpose or her friendships. it was a refreshing example in ya to have a relationship that didn’t become all consuming for the female mc. .
.
.
read my full spoiler free review of #theblackcoats on youngadultreads.com {link in bio} 🖤🗝♟
.
.
.
the black coats is a contemporary novel about thea, a grieving high school girl who joins the black coats (a highly secretive society) to exact vengeance on men who hurt girls and women. thea must confront how far she’s willing to go for justice and what type of justice she deserves. 🧥🧐🖤
.
.
.

text:
warum finde ich ein buch so verdammt gut, bei dem die hauptfigur mich total herablassend behandelt??? ganz einfach: weil der autor john niven heißt und die hauptfigur der skrupellose musikmanager steven stelfox ist, der wirklich ein echtes arschloch ist, dabei zum glück aber erschreckend unterhaltsam. ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀ ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
steven stelfox hat schon in nivens ersten buch 'kill your friends' die hauptrolle gespielt – einen musikmanager, der über leichen geht. 20 jahre sind seitdem vergangen und steven stelfox hat es geschafft: er ist steinreich, hängt auf luxusvillen ab und zieht dort über die dummheit der menschen her. denn eines muss man wissen: eigentlich hat nur er den durchblick, alle anderen gehören zum naiven pöbel, der sich nur zu gern verarschen lässt. ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
sein neuster auftrag: er soll sich um den weltstar lucius du pre kümmern. der typ ist so eine art micheal jackson-abklatsch: er lebt auf einem freizeitparkähnlichen anwesen, wurde vom vater misshandelt und hat probleme mit seinem aussehen – seine hautfarbe ist ihm zu weiß. ja, so in etwa funktioniert der humor in diesem buch. und lucius du pre soll pädophil sein, was jetzt droht herauszukommen. steven stelfox soll es regeln, die plattenfirma vorm ruin retten und natürlich kennt er dabei keine moral, keine grenzen und kein gewissen. ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
‚kill ´em all` ist eine düstere geschichte voller arschlöcher, die provoziert und grenzen überschreitet. john niven wirft hier einen bitterbösen blick auf die musikindustrie und hat zugleich eine zynische gesellschaftskritik geschrieben. es geht um fake news, #metoo genauso wie um den brexit und donald trump (steven stelfox ist natürlich ein fan). das buch ist brutal, derb und gnadenlos sarkastisch – unbedingt lesen. gesa 👧🏼
.
.
.
.
.
#johnniven #killemall #stevenstelfox #satire #buchtipp #gesellschaftskritik #michaeljackson #heynehardcore #kultroman #donaldtrump #bestseller #kunstblut #blut #musik #bookstagram #michaeljackson

sein neuster auftrag: er soll sich um den weltstar lucius du pre kümmern. der typ ist so eine a micheal jackson-abklatsch: er lebt auf einem freizeitparkähnlichen anwesen, wurde vom vater misshandelt und hat probleme mit seinem aussehen – seine hautfarbe ist ihm zu weiß. ja, so in etwa funktionie der humor in diesem buch. und lucius du pre soll pädophil sein, was jetzt droht herauszukommen. steven stelfox soll es regeln, die plattenfirma vorm ruin retten und natürlich kennt er dabei keine moral, keine grenzen und kein gewissen. ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
‚kill ´em all` ist eine düstere geschichte voller arschlöcher, die provozie und grenzen überschreitet. john niven wirft hier einen bitterbösen blick auf die musikindustrie und hat zugleich eine zynische gesellschaftskritik geschrieben. es geht um fake news,  genauso wie um den brexit und donald trump (steven stelfox ist natürlich ein fan). das buch ist brutal, derb und gnadenlos sarkastisch – unbedingt lesen. gesa 👧🏼

text:
the first day of black history month will always be dedicated to my unsung hero. ⁣
⁣
betty jean owens is an african american woman who was brutally raped by four white men in tallahassee, florida in 1959. her trial was significant in florida, and the south as a whole, because the white men were given life sentences for their crimes. this severe of a sentencing had not occurred for white men in the south accused of raping black women previous to owens' case.⁣
⁣
 above: the first picture is of florida a&m students sitting in the courtroom during betty's trial. the second picture is a photo of the cover of the 1959 may edition of the famuan. the picture on the cover of the famuan is of over one thousand florida a&m students who gathered on the university’s quadrangle to demand justice for betty jean owens. the cover picture was taken on may 4, 1959 two days after the incident. ⁣
⁣
the first time i heard the story of betty jean owens it changed my life and it really hit home. i heard her story for the first time my freshmen year during my african-america history class. my professor was giving a lecture on the civil rights movement, and how we weren't far-removed from that era. he said most of the people who fought for our rights are still living amongst us. he began to tell the story of betty jean owens. after telling her story, my professor told us about how recently during a commencement ceremony, the president of florida a&m called betty owens out of the audience to render homage. being from tallahassee this story was interesting to me because i had never heard of betty jean owens.⁣
⁣
 at the time, i was living with my grandparents, so when i got home i asked my grandmother (who's also from tallahassee) if she had ever heard the story of betty jean owens. before i could tell her what i learned that day in class she began to cry. i asked, "grandma, what's wrong?" she said, "i am betty jean owens." 🙊 ⁣
⁣
to learn more about her story or to write a #letter2betty click the link in my bio. 🙏🏾⁣
⁣
#blackhistorymonth #negrohistoryweek1926 #payinghomage ✊🏾 #bettyjeanowens ❤️ #metoo
name: Amontè L. Martin

pre_proc_tweet:
the first day of black history month will always be dedicated to my unsung hero. ⁣
⁣
betty jean owens is an african american woman who was brutally raped by four white men in tallahassee, florida in 1959. her trial was significan not in florida, and the south as a whole, because the white men were given life sentences for their crimes. this severe of a sentencing had not occurred for white men in the south accused of raping black women previous to owens' case.⁣
⁣
 above: the first picture is of florida a&m students sitting in the couroom during betty's trial. the second picture is a photo of the cover of the 1959 may edition of the famuan. the picture on the cover of the famuan is of over one thousand florida a&m students who gathered on the university’s quadrangle to demand justice for betty jean owens. the cover picture was taken on may 4, 1959 two days after the incident. ⁣
⁣
the first time i heard the story of betty jean owens it changed my life and it really hit home. i heard her story for the first time my freshmen year during my african-america history class. my professor was giving a lecture on the civil rights movement, and how we weren't far-removed from that era. he said most of the people who fought for our rights are still living amongst us. he began to tell the story of betty jean owens. after telling her story, my professor told us about how recently during a commencement ceremony, the president of florida a&m called betty owens out of the audience to render homage. being from tallahassee this story was interesting to me because i had never heard of betty jean owens.⁣
⁣
 at the time, i was living with my grandparents, so when i got home i asked my grandmother (who's also from tallahassee) if she had ever heard the story of betty jean owens. before i could tell her what i learned that day in class she began to cry. i asked, "grandma, what's wrong?" she said, "i am betty jean owens." 🙊 ⁣
⁣
to learn more about her story or to write a  click the link in my bio. 🙏🏾⁣
⁣
   ✊🏾  ❤️

text:
let's chat about counseling...shall we? 
make sure you have your hot beverage of choice...this might be awhile. 
when i was younger i went through a lot of abuse. emotionally, mentally, and physically. 
kids (even adults) blame themselves and have a tendency to think that something with themselves is wrong. they aren't smart enough, they don't listen well enough, they are just plain dumb and stupid. 
this manifests and can lead to poor coping skills, anxiety, depression, eating disorders, self harm, etc. 
my first tip of advice is to leave the situation if it is a possibility to do so. trust me, much much easier said than done. if leaving isn't a feasible option, then counseling is a great option. 
do your research and see what would best fit you and what you need. what works with your insurance or maybe you won't even use insurance. 
after lots of persuasion from those closest to me and knowing that life shouldn't be like this; i broke down. i reached out. i opened up to a trained human being about all of my thoughts, feelings, and misconceptions. 
one of the best decisions i ever made for myself. that paired with other life changes..i used to be a pessimistic, hopeless, depressed,  self harming, lay around and cry all the time gal. i wanted to die and not have to deal with this life anymore. i felt worthless and very undeserving. 
through counseling i've been given tips and tricks to how to navigate what i'm feeling, how to use coping skills in a healthy way, plus i have another human i can confide in and trust. 
like i said, it took years before i accepted i needed help. maybe now isn't your time. maybe this can be the nudge to help you consider counseling.  learn from me: even when it doesn't feel like it will be okay, it will be okay.

text:
happy #blackhistorymonth! all through february, we'll be highlighting black women leaders from our community, politics, the arts, and education. today, we honor the iconic shirley chisolm, a pioneering american politician who paved the way for women and women of color in elected office.
✨
chisolm was the first black woman elected to the united states congress and served new york's 12th congressional district from 1969-1983. in 1972, she became the first black candidate for any major american party's presidential nomination, and the first woman to run for the democratic party's presidential nomination.
✨
it goes without saying that chisolm changed the scope of possibility for united states government and leadership; she is arguably one of the most important figures in american political history.

text:
those who really know me, know it's no surprise to anyone how much i love jesus. i want others to experience that love. i want my children to grow and have a relationship with christ. one of the greatest things i have learned as a christian since moving to baltimore is how christians can be ones that make big a difference in the face of sickening and gross injustices. .
.
growing up in the south, i will admit, i may have been shielded from it. jesus is amazing yes, and there's nothing wrong with reading or listening to uplifting and encouraging things. however, we need to be careful that in doing that we don't forget to educate ourselves on the hard things, the dirty, the gross, the things we so often want to pretend aren't there. that isn't what jesus did, and if we want to truly make a change, we must not hide away, keeping ourselves safe in our little bubble. we must be willing to listen to, read about, and learn about the hard issues too. and do. jesus and his love is for all people. even the ones we wish we could pretend don't exist sometimes. hard to hear, but often times true..
.
these are the things and issues jesus desperately wants to change through his people... through love, hope, grace, peace, and justice. so, i am thankful that god brought me here. it's truly opened my eyes, and my heart 💗
.
.
. .
.
.
.
.
.

text:
an·he·do·ni·a (noun) "the inability to feel pleasure from activities usually found enjoyable." this is the worst part of living with major depression (in my experience). it rides the waves of my emotional triggers and challenges my peace of mind.🤦🏽‍♀️
what's the blessing in that? challenges provide us with opportunities to win! 
start with a deep breath. *inhale....exhale* now ask yourself: what can i do to nurture my inner queen (divinity) today? accommodate her by doing the smallest task possible. repeat. win.✔️ success is nothing more than the sum of consistent efforts (big or small) to accomplish a specific goal. you've got this. we've got this. peace and light.✨ love, ✊🏼✊🏾✊🏿
📸: @shaheedrahmxn

#blackhistorymonth 
today we honor: #sojournertruth 
fun facts: • sojourner truth’s birth name was isabella baumfree. she changed her name because she felt a divine calling to fight for freedom everywhere she could possibly get to. •she escaped slavery, and after doing so, one of her children was sold illegally to a slave owner. truth’s bravery helped her get her son back after taking legal action and being one of the first black women to win a court case against a white man. •she delivered “aren’t/ain’t i a woman” which would challenge how the black woman is seen in society. 
for the above mentioned and much more @newwitchesunite thanks #sojournertruth for her amazing work of activism.

text:
trigger warning: sexual assault. i love the idea of celebrating a new year and a fresh start, but there’s a pretty big part of me that has hated january for years because of the memories it invokes. i kept seeing the “january was a tough year but we made it” meme all over my feed this morning and i had an “aha” moment that i wanted to share 💙 yesterday marked 12 years since i testified against a man who sexually abused me for much of my life. but it also marked 12 years of safety, freedom and healing. for many years, i would allow myself to take january 31 as a day for me. a day of wallowing to be alone, sad, angry or scared. but yesterday i went to work…and i took a yoga class…and i ate wings at the bar and laughed with my husband. and as i write this i’m crying my under eye patches off (which is funny, but also sad because they’re expensive), but i’m not crying because i’m sad. i’m crying because it was the first january 31st in 12 years that i didn’t let this horrible man consume my thoughts for an entire day(🙌🏼). i lived my life as if it were any other day. i lived it like a survivor and not a victim. this is not to say that i forget the past, and it definitely does not mean that i won’t have hard days moving forward, but january has been a “tough year” for me for over a decade and i’ve got to say, january 2019 wasn’t so bad...and it's partly because of these two goobers in this photo. mike’s patience with me and his willingness to make me happy never go unnoticed. i treasure caitlin’s thoughtfulness, honesty and comedic relief as a friend and a business partner. i fucking love you guys and i can’t believe i found you 💙 .
.
.
photos @ashtonkelleyphotography

text:
📢📢jan fabre 😈 😈: violences et harcèlement
discussion à la générale nord est organisée par la permanence le 31/01 à 20h

témoignage pour l'occasion de tabitha cholet concernant sa démission et dénonciation à cause du comportement du chorégraphe.
en septembre, suite au mouvement #metoo, une vingtaine d'interprètes a dénoncé dans une lettre ouverte, ci-jointe, les violences dont elles et ils étaient victimes depuis des années.

le théâtre de la bastille a limité les contestations de cette programmation en les dénigrant. ce qui est incompréhensible.

nous sommes à fond solidaires du combat mené par ses artistes 👊👊
la suite est à venir car d'autres pièces chorégraphiques de yan fabre vont être jouées au cours de l'année 2019 sur le territoire parisien comme à la villette.
